09010nam a22009615i 9780228013471DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280134717 a10.1515/97802280134712doi  a(DE-B1597)657871  a(OCoLC)1298288189  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSCI0300002bisacsh04a338.0971922300aExtractive Industry and the Sustainability of Canada's Arctic Communities /ced. by Dave Natcher, Brenda Parlee, Frances Abele, Chris Southcott. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b35 photos, 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tExtractive Industry and the Sustainability of Canada’s Arctic Communities: An Introduction -- tResource Revenue Allocation Strategies and Indigenous Community Sustainable Development -- tMining Economies, Mining Families: The Impacts of Extractive Industries on Economic and Human Development in the Eastern Subarctic -- tLocal Benefits of Education, Training, and Employment with Resource Industries -- tFinding Space for Subsistence and Extractive Resource Development in Northern Canada -- tThe FIFO Social Overlap: Success and Pitfalls of Long-Distance Commuting in the Mining Sector -- tReframing Benefits: Indigenous Women and Resource Governance in Northern Canada -- t“It’s a precarious situation”: Situating Housing First Within the Resource Dependent Economy in Yellowknife, Northwest Territorie -- tEnvironmental Legacies: Mine Remediation Policy and Practice in Northern Canada -- tFacilitating Sustainable Waste Management in a Northern Community and Resource Development Context at Happy Valley- Goose Bay, Labrador -- tThe Social Economy and Resource Governance in Nunavut -- tImpacts of Mining on Well-Being: A Disconnect between Theory and Practice -- tMeasuring the Social and Economic Impacts of Extractive Industry in the Arctic: Developing Baseline Social Indicators for the Inuvialuit Settlement Region -- tMeasuring Social Impacts: Building Tools for Understanding Community Well-Being -- tWhat Must Happen for Extractive Industry to Help the Sustainability of Northern Communities? -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern treaties, increased self-government, new environmental assessment rules, co-management bodies, and increased recognition and respect of Indigenous rights make it possible for northern communities to exert some control over extractive industries. Whether these industries can increase the well-being and sustainability of Canada’s Arctic communities, however, is still open to question.Extractive Industry and the Sustainability of Canada’s Arctic Communities delves into the final research findings of the Resources and Sustainable Development in the Arctic project which attempted to determine what was required for extractive industry to benefit northern communities. Drawing on case studies, this book explores how northern communities can capture and distribute a fairer share of financial benefits, how they can use extractive activities for business development, the problems and possibilities of employment and training opportunities, and the impacts on gender relations. It also considers fly-in fly-out work patterns, subsistence activities, housing, post-mine clean-up activities, waste management, and ways of monitoring positive and negative impacts. While extractive industries could potentially help improve the sustainability of Canada’s Arctic, many issues stand in the way, most notably power imbalances that limit the ability of Indigenous Peoples to equitably participate in their governance.Extractive Industry and the Sustainability of Canada’s Arctic Communities emphasizes the general need to determine how new institutions and processes, which are largely imported from the south, can be adapted to allow for a more authentic participation from the Indigenous Peoples of Canada’s Arctic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcology. 0aEconomic history. 0aIndigenous peoples-Social conditions. 0aSustainable development. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh1 aAbele, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbele, Frances, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAndrew, Leon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelayneh, Anteneh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoutet, Jean-Sébastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavin, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalseg, Sheena Kennedy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDance, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladstone, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodfrey, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodgkins, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeeling, Arn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeske, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemelin, Harvey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemus-Lauzon, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v